        "The case for a wealth tax begins with a simple observation: the current tax system is structurally incapable of taxing the richest Americans. ProPublica's analysis of IRS data revealed that between 2014 and 2018, the 25 wealthiest Americans paid a \"true tax rate\" of only 3.4% on their wealth growth of $401 billion. Warren Buffett famously pays a lower effective tax rate than his secretary. This is not a bug \u2014 it is a feature of a system that taxes income but not wealth, allowing billionaires to grow fortunes through unrealized capital gains that may never be taxed.\n\nThe scale of the problem demands a structural solution. The top 0.1% of Americans now hold more wealth than the bottom 80% combined. The top 1% holds $44.6 trillion in wealth, more than the entire middle class. This concentration has accelerated dramatically: the wealth share of the top 0.1% has roughly tripled since the 1970s while median household wealth has barely budged. A modest annual tax on extreme wealth \u2014 say 2% on fortunes above $50 million and 3% above $1 billion, as proposed by Senator Elizabeth Warren \u2014 would generate an estimated $2.75 trillion over ten years according to economists Emmanuel Saez and Gabriel Zucman.\n\nBeyond revenue, a wealth tax addresses the democratic crisis of concentrated wealth. When individuals can spend hundreds of millions on political campaigns, fund think tanks to shape public discourse, and lobby for favorable regulations, the political system itself becomes captured. A wealth tax is not merely fiscal policy; it is a democratic corrective. The historical precedent is strong: the most prosperous period in American history, the postwar era, coincided with a top marginal income tax rate above 90% and an effective tax system that prevented extreme concentration. The question is not whether we can tax wealth \u2014 Switzerland has done so successfully for over a century. The question is whether we will.",
