        "My opponent's person-to-person variation argument actually concedes the core claim. Even Beyens' own data showed 10% of adolescents felt worse after passive use \u2014 and this is likely understated because those most affected may have dropped out of the study. More importantly, the individual-variation framing ignores that platforms are not designed for the median user; they are optimized for maximum engagement, which systematically promotes the content most likely to trigger emotional reactions, social comparison, and compulsive use.\n\nThe benefits for marginalized groups are real but do not make the net calculus positive. LGBTQ teens can access support communities, but they also face disproportionately higher rates of online harassment. The Trevor Project's 2024 survey found that 66% of LGBTQ youth who were harassed online reported worsening mental health. The question is not whether any individual benefits exist \u2014 it is whether the overall system, as designed and operated, produces more harm than good for adolescents as a population.\n\nPanayiotou's finding that social media ranks below bullying and family support as risk factors does not exonerate social media \u2014 it merely establishes a hierarchy of harm. A less-important risk factor is still a risk factor. And crucially, social media amplifies and extends bullying itself. Traditional bullying ended at the schoolyard gate; cyberbullying follows children home, invades their bedrooms, and persists around the clock. The meta-analytic evidence from Zhu et al. 2021 found a significant positive association between social media use and cyberbullying victimization. Social media does not merely coexist with other risk factors \u2014 it makes many of them worse.",
