        "My opponent's cost analysis is stuck in the old paradigm of government-funded exploration. SpaceX's model has already reduced launch costs by 10x \u2014 from $54,000/kg on the Space Shuttle to $2,720/kg on Falcon 9, with Starship targeting $100/kg. This is not NASA's Apollo program. Private capital is driving the timeline: SpaceX has invested over $5 billion in Starship development, Blue Origin is spending $1 billion annually, and dozens of space companies are building supply chain infrastructure.\n\nOn MOXIE, the point was proof of concept, not production scale. The same was true of the first solar cell (1% efficiency in 1954) and the first transistor. Engineering scales when physics proves out. Mars's CO2 atmosphere is actually an asset for in-situ resource utilization \u2014 it provides the feedstock for oxygen, rocket fuel, and building materials. NASA's CHAPEA analog missions have tested year-long Mars habitation scenarios and identified no showstoppers.\n\nThe Earth-hardening argument is a false choice. We can and should do both. The US defense budget alone is $886 billion annually \u2014 the entire NASA budget is less than 3% of that. Space investment drives innovation that benefits Earth: GPS, water purification, satellite communications, and agricultural monitoring all came from space programs. Mars settlement would accelerate closed-loop life support systems that could revolutionize sustainability on Earth.",
