        "The FOR side wants to win on aspiration: if something is not forbidden by physics, we should treat it as feasible and make it a priority. That is not the resolution. \"Feasible\" means realistically achievable with demonstrated pathways, not just imaginable in theory. And \"should be a priority\" means it deserves to outrank competing uses of money, talent, and political attention right now. They never met either burden. MOXIE was a tiny technology demo, not a settlement-scale life-support system. CHAPEA is an Earth analog, not proof humans can survive years of radiation, isolation, delayed communication, and no evacuation on Mars.\n\nTheir analogies fail on the details that matter most. The ISS sits in low Earth orbit, under Earth's protective environment, with constant resupply and emergency return. Starlink is a communications business built around a planet already full of industry, labor, hospitals, and supply chains. Mars settlement is the simultaneous creation of an entire permanent human ecosystem in the most hostile environment humans have ever attempted to inhabit. A list of past achievements does not prove this particular one is ready, affordable, or prudently prioritized.\n\nOn extinction risk, a fragile Mars outpost dependent on Earth for years or decades is not a serious backup for civilization; it is another failure point. If the goal is reducing existential risk, Earth-hardening is cheaper, faster, and more comprehensive: pandemic prevention, nuclear risk reduction, asteroid deflection, resilient infrastructure, food security, and climate adaptation protect billions now and address the most plausible threats first.\n\nMars settlement may be a long-term dream, but the resolution asks whether it is feasible and should be a priority for humanity now. On the evidence in this debate, it is neither. The FOR side proved interest, ambition, and momentum. They did not prove settlement-scale feasibility, and they did not prove priority over better, nearer, and more effective alternatives. Vote AGAINST.",
