      content:
        "The affirmative is asking you to vote for two claims at once: that lab-grown meat will replace conventional animal agriculture within the next few decades, and that it should. They have not proved either. What they offered is a trajectory story: costs falling, approvals beginning, facilities being announced. But a trajectory is not a takeover. The decisive evidence is that cultivated meat remains unproven at commodity scale, biologically fragile, capital intensive, and deeply dependent on ideal conditions that do not resemble the global food system it is supposed to replace.\n\nFalling prototype prices do not answer the real question: can you produce millions of tons of meat consistently, safely, and cheaply enough to displace conventional agriculture worldwide? The economics at industrial scale are still unresolved, contamination risk remains intrinsic to cell culture, and scale-up in biology is not like scale-up in software. If the core production model is still this uncertain, then \"replace within a few decades\" is not a forecast. It is speculation.\n\nThe environmental argument collapses once you leave the best-case scenario. Recent life-cycle analysis shows cultivated meat can have higher impacts than conventional meat if production depends on energy-intensive purification and standard grid electricity. The affirmative answered reform by saying it has not solved everything. That is not a warrant for betting the food system on a technology that may fail on cost, scale, and even emissions.\n\nIf cultivated meat becomes a useful supplement, that is fine. But the resolution is much larger: replacement, in the near-term historical window of a few decades. On that claim, the affirmative never got past aspiration. They proved prototypes, not displacement; moral urgency, not operational success. Vote AGAINST.",
      round: 3,
