      content: "The negative's final position is revealing: they agree that capital gains should be reformed, inheritance taxes strengthened, loopholes closed, and antitrust enforced. They simply deny that these measures constitute \"preventing\" extreme wealth concentration. But this is a distinction without a difference. If you reform capital gains taxation to capture unrealized gains, strengthen inheritance taxes to prevent dynastic wealth transmission, close the carried-interest loophole, enforce antitrust to break up monopoly rent extraction, and implement international tax cooperation to prevent capital flight — you have, in effect, prevented the mechanisms that create and sustain billionaire-level wealth concentration. The resolution asks whether concentration \"should be prevented through taxation or structural reform.\" My opponent has endorsed every component of that prescription while denying the label.\n\nOn the democratic evidence, my opponent focuses on whether the rich \"always\" win policy fights. This misses the structural point entirely. The issue is not whether plutocrats win every vote — it is whether the existence of extreme wealth concentration systematically biases the political system. The evidence is unambiguous: dark money spending grew from $5 million to over $1 billion in two decades. Lobbying expenditures exceed $3.7 billion annually. Danny Yagan's finding that the top 400 families pay an effective federal income tax rate of 9.6% — lower than middle-class families — is itself proof that wealth has captured the tax system. You do not get a 9.6% effective rate by accident; you get it through decades of successful lobbying for preferential treatment of capital income. That is the mechanism by which wealth concentration perpetuates itself, exactly as Piketty's r > g framework predicts.\n\nOn philanthropy, the negative's best example — the pneumococcal AMC — was designed and funded primarily by governments through Gavi, with the Gates Foundation contributing alongside sovereign donors. This proves that public institutions are the essential actors; billionaire philanthropy is supplementary, not foundational. More importantly, the debate is not about whether any billionaire has ever done anything useful with their money. It is about whether a system that allows unlimited wealth accumulation produces better outcomes than one that redistributes more broadly through democratic institutions. The historical evidence overwhelmingly favors the latter: the period of greatest shared prosperity in American history — the postwar decades — was also the period of highest marginal tax rates, strongest unions, and least wealth concentration. The resolution is correct: extreme wealth concentration is harmful, and structural reform is warranted. Vote FOR.",
